Staying indoors is the new normalcy¶

In this data analysis, I am inspecting mobility trends based on Google mobility reports, which collect percentage changes in movement from the pre-pandemic baseline. The "baseline" is the median value from the five weeks Jan 3 Feb 6, 2020, as defined in the Google Mobility Reports.

There are six types of mobility measures in the reports:

  • retail and recreation
  • grocery and pharmacy
  • parks
  • transit stations
  • workplaces
  • residential

# load data

# region data so we can map each state to its region
region = pd.read_csv("state-region.csv")

# merge data from two years
df20 = pd.read_csv("2020_US_Region_Mobility_Report.csv")
df21 = pd.read_csv("2021_US_Region_Mobility_Report.csv")
df = pd.concat([df20, df21])
df = df.drop_duplicates(subset=["sub_region_1", "sub_region_2", "date", "retail_and_recreation_percent_change_from_baseline"], keep="last")
df = df.merge(region, left_on='sub_region_1', right_on='State')

# format datetime data
df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["date"])

# create a list that contains column names of the 6 major mobility patterns
mobility_ls = ["retail_and_recreation_percent_change_from_baseline",
"grocery_and_pharmacy_percent_change_from_baseline",
"parks_percent_change_from_baseline",
"transit_stations_percent_change_from_baseline",
"workplaces_percent_change_from_baseline",
"residential_percent_change_from_baseline"]

Based on the above results, no normal distributions were observed and all distributions are full of outliers.

Distributions of percent change of grocery and pharmacy, parks, transit stations, and residential areas are positively skewed. The first two are leptokurtic, meaning that a distinct peak can be observed near the mean.

The distribution of workplaces mobility percent change is negatively skewed, leaving a long tail on the left side of the distribution. It has the smallest standard deviation and kurtosis, indicating that it has fewer extreme outliers.

The distribution of park mobility percent change has the highest mean, max, range, standard deviation and skewness. This might be resulting from the multiple missing values and outliers above 100.

overallUsCopy = overallUs.reset_index()
now = overallUsCopy[(overallUsCopy.date >= pd.to_datetime("2021-04-07")) & (overallUsCopy.date <= pd.to_datetime("2021-05-07"))].groupby(["date"]).median()

change_col = [[], [], [], [], [], []]
for j in range(len(mobility_ls)):
    m = mobility_ls[j]
    change = now[m].mean()
    change_col[j].append(change)
        
recGap = pd.DataFrame()
recGap["retail_recreation_change_diff"] = change_col[0]
recGap["groce_pharm_change_diff"] = change_col[1]
recGap["parks_change_diff"] = change_col[2]
recGap["transit_change_diff"] = change_col[3]
recGap["workplaces_change_diff"] = change_col[4]
recGap["residential_change_diff"] = change_col[5]
recGap.to_csv("clean-overall-us-avg-mobility-data.csv")

  • A big plummet in April can be seen in all charts except for residential percent change.

  • A surge in March, when covid cases just started to rise and many people were panic buying, can be observed in percent change of retail and recreation and grocery and pharmacy.

  • Percent change of retail and recreation, transit stations and workplaces declined to around -40% in April.

  • While most mobility patterns have climbed back to the baseline of 0, the percent change of workplaces is still below -20%.

(Missing values in the original data were neglected in the above charts.)

Average mobility patterns in each region¶

I am comparing the average mobility in the past month and that in the beginning of the pandemic.

Average mobility in the past month: average between April 7, 2021 and May 7, 2021, last collected day when analysis was done.

Average mobility in a year before: average between April 7, 2020 and May 7, 2020.

In [15]:
# west: green
# northeast: blue
# midwest: yellow
# south: pink
colors = {'West':'#06d6a0', 'South': '#ef476f', 'Northeast':'#118ab2', 'Midwest': '#ffd166'}

before = states[(states.date >= pd.to_datetime("2020-04-07")) & (states.date <= pd.to_datetime("2020-05-07"))]
now = states[(states.date >= pd.to_datetime("2021-04-07")) & (states.date <= pd.to_datetime("2021-05-07"))]

state_col = [[], [], [], [], [], []]
change_col = [[], [], [], [], [], []]

for i in range(len(state_ls)):
    s = state_ls[i]
    selnow = now[now.sub_region_1 == s].groupby(["date"]).median()
    selbefore = before[before.sub_region_1 == s].groupby(["date"]).median()
    for j in range(len(mobility_ls)):
        m = mobility_ls[j]
        change = selnow[m].mean() - selbefore[m].mean()
        state_col[j].append(s)
        change_col[j].append(change)
        
recGap = pd.DataFrame()
recGap["state"] = state_col[0]
recGap["retail_recreation_change_diff"] = change_col[0]
recGap["groce_pharm_change_diff"] = change_col[1]
recGap["parks_change_diff"] = change_col[2]
recGap["transit_change_diff"] = change_col[3]
recGap["workplaces_change_diff"] = change_col[4]
recGap["residential_change_diff"] = change_col[5]

recGap = recGap.merge(region, left_on='state', right_on='State')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(25, 50), nrows=6)
l = ["retail_recreation_change_diff","groce_pharm_change_diff","parks_change_diff","transit_change_diff","workplaces_change_diff","residential_change_diff"]

for i in range(len(l)):
    mobility = l[i]
    recGap.sort_values(['Region', mobility], inplace=True)
    recGap.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True)
    d = recGap[['state', 'Region', mobility]]
    ax[i].bar(d.state, d[mobility], color=d.Region.map(colors))
    ax[i].set_title(mobility, fontsize=20)
    ax[i].tick_params(axis='x', labelrotation = 45, labelsize = 16)
fig.tight_layout(pad=1.2)
plt.show()

Compared with the beginning of the pandemic, average mobility patterns this year increase in almost all states by more than 10%. Alaska and Minnesota are the only two exceptions in the park mobility category. And residential mobility patterns decrease by around 10%.

  • In all states, average percent changes in workplaces remain negative and that in residential areas remain positive, with D.C. having the most significant decline in workplaces and the largest increase in residential areas.

  • In retail and recreation and grocery and pharmacy categories, about half of the states in northeast and west regions saw negative mobility percent changes. In contrast, most states in the south and midwest regions, such as Idaho, Iowa, South Dakota, Mississippi, Missouri and Montana, saw positive mobility percent changes.

  • Average mobility pattern in parks surpass/recover to the baseline in almost all states except for D.C. and Hawaii, where the numbers are still around -20%. But keep in mind that missing values in this column are up to almost 80%.

  • All states in the northeast region have a negative percent change in transit stations. In the other regions, we're seeing about half of the states having negative percent changes and the other half having positive percent changes.

  • D.C. has the most significant drop, below -40%, in retail, grocery, transit and workplaces and the highest average mobility in residential areas. Mobility patterns in Hawaii, Vermont, and Massachusetts are also way below pre-pandemic levels.

Conclusion¶

  • As vaccine rollout has begun and lockdowns have eased, U.S. average mobility patterns in retail and recreation, grocery and pharmacy and transit stations have climbed back to pre-pandemic levels. At the same time, mobility in workplaces is still around -20%, way below the baseline. But the trends are not universal across the country.

  • Compared with the beginning of the pandemic, current average mobility patterns of retail and recreation, grocery and pharmacy, parks, workplaces and transit stations increase in almost all states by more than 10%. And residential mobility patterns decrease by around 10%.

  • However, some of the mobility patterns haven't recovered to the pre-pandemic levels yet. In all states, average percent changes in workplaces remain negative and that in residential areas remain positive, with D.C. having the most significant decline in workplaces and the largest increase in residential areas.

  • In retail and recreation and grocery and pharmacy categories, about half of the states in the northeast and west regions are still seeing a negative mobility percent change, while most states in the south and midwest regions, such as Idaho, Iowa, South Dakota, Mississippi, Missouri and Montana, are seeing positive mobility percent changes.

  • Average mobility in park is way above the baseline in almost all states except for D.C., Florida, Hawaii and North Dakota. But keep in mind that missing values in this column are up to nearly 80%.

  • A negative percent change in transit stations can be observed in all states in the northeast region.

  • The percentage of people working remotely highly correlates with changes in mobility patterns. States with more percentage of people reporting being able to telework have lower than normal mobility in retail and recreation, grocery and pharmacy, transit stations and workplaces.

  • For example, the above mobility patterns in D.C., where more than 50% of people reporting being able to telework, are still below -40%. And that in Hawaii, Vermont and Massachusetts are also way below pre-pandemic levels.
